After the liberal international order
Cambridge—many analysts believe the liberal international order ended with China's rise and the election of US President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he strive to revive it?
Perhaps the outcome won't be that, but he must find some alternative.
Critics point out that the US order since 1945 was neither global nor always very liberal, and this is correct.
It excluded more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and included many authoritarian states.
The US hegemony has always been exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful country must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided — and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic goal of the Biden administration should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in the handling of different issues.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 21st century, both countries were unable to balance American power, while the United States imposed its will on sovereignty in pursuit of liberal values.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without UN Security Council approval.
It also supported a 2005 UN General Assembly resolution on "Responsibility to Protect," aimed at providing protection for citizens suffering cruel treatment at the hands of their own governments — later, the United States used this principle in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as hubris by Americans in the post-Cold War era — for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to a regime change, Russia and China felt deceived — while defenders of the action describe it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Regardless, the growing power of China and Russia has more strictly limited liberal interventionist actions.
So what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty stipulated in the UN Charter, which states that states can only use force for self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the situation of occupying neighboring territories by force has been very rare, and once it occurs, it incurs high costs through sanctions (as seen in Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled countries, and political cooperation has also successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of a rules-based order remains crucial.
Specifically in economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Long before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the WTO.
The result will be the decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is threatened.
Although China complains that the U.S. is blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. position is consistent with its claims of sovereignty.
After all, China has prevented Google, Facebook, and Twitter from operating in China for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules would help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
At the same time, despite the outbreak of this current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
In contrast, interdependence in the ecological field creates insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, because the threats are transboundary.
Regardless of the setbacks to economic globalization, environmental globalization will continue, because it is subject to biological and physical laws, which are unaffected by contemporary geopolitical logic.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no country is capable of solving them independently.
On issues such as the 2019 coronavirus pandemic and climate change, power also has what is called a positive-sum dimension.
Under such circumstances, merely thinking about exercising power over others is insufficient.
We must also think about exercising power in cooperation with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are helpful to us and to others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this has not affected cooperation between the US and China.
Biden's challenge is whether the US and China can cooperate to produce global public goods, while at the same time engaging in competition in traditional great power areas.
The cyberspace is a new and important issue —— because it is partly transnational but also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Free speech and privacy rules for the internet can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As suggested by the Global Cyber Stability Committee, if authoritarian regimes also wish to achieve connectivity, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the fundamental structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
But when they use proxies to conduct information warfare or interfere in elections (which infringes on sovereignty), norms must be strengthened through rules such as those negotiated between the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War to limit escalation in maritime incidents (although ideological hostility remains).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Adhering to the free values of cyberspace does not mean that the United States is unilaterally disarming.
Instead, the United States should distinguish between permissible open persuasion through soft power and hard power such as covert information warfare, and it must certainly retaliate when the other side launches covert information warfare.
It may allow Russia and China to publicly broadcast programs and radio, but secret acts of uniformity such as manipulating social media are not allowed.
Moreover, the U.S. Congress will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Public opinion polls show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values its values.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue is whether the United States can cooperate with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while simultaneously working with a broader range of countries to manage rule-based international systems needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
